Every initial public offering is marketed in two ways:=09=E2=80=9CThis comp=
any is good=E2=80=9D: This is the story that the IPO prospectus will tell, =
and that the company will tell in roadshow meetings with potential investor=
s. The company has a good business, a good product,=C2=A0smart managers, st=
rong financial results, so if you are a long-term fundamental investor you =
should buy some stock.=09=E2=80=9CThis stock will trade up=E2=80=9D: This i=
s the story that the marginal investor in the IPO wants to hear. The compan=
y is selling X million shares in the IPO, there are orders for 10X million =
shares, there are a lot of retail investors who would love to buy it but ca=
n=E2=80=99t get into the IPO, and so, when the stock opens for trading on t=
he day after the IPO, lots of people =E2=80=94=C2=A0the retail investors, t=
he people who put in the 9X million orders that weren=E2=80=99t filled =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0will buy it in the aftermarket. There is a lot of demand, not e=
nough supply, so the stock will go up.That second story is, to some degree,=
 self-fulfilling. The company=E2=80=99s banks will call an investor to ask=
=C2=A0=E2=80=9Chow much do you want to buy in this IPO?=E2=80=9D The invest=
or will say =E2=80=9Cwell how is it going?=E2=80=9D The correct answer is n=
ot =E2=80=9Cwe=E2=80=99ve got orders for 80% of the shares, so it would rea=
lly help if you=E2=80=99d put in a big order for the other 20%.=E2=80=9D Th=
e answer the investor wants is more like =E2=80=9Cwe=E2=80=99ve got orders =
for 1,000% of the shares, but if you put in a big order we=E2=80=99ll see w=
hat we can do for you.=E2=80=9D The more demand the investors think there i=
s, the more demand there will actually be: Investors want to buy into IPOs =
that=C2=A0don=E2=80=99t=C2=A0need their money, because those are the ones t=
hat will trade up.
  [1]
We have talked a few times about Bill Ackman=E2=80=99s plans for a US publi=
cly listed closed-end fund, Pershing Square USA Ltd., or PSUS. He has=C2=A0=
talked about=C2=A0raising $25 billion in its IPO.=C2=A0He=E2=80=99s marketi=
ng that IPO now, and the roadshow is nearing its end, with the deal set to =
price on Monday. So far, uh, it doesn=E2=80=99t look like $25 billion.
  [2]
=C2=A0The revised target is more like $2.5 billion to $4 billion, with room=
 to grow from there but=C2=A0a hard cap of $10 billion.I suppose you could =
tell a version of Story 2 here that would go something like this: =E2=80=9C=
If the market gets the idea that PSUS will be a $25 billion IPO, people wil=
l anchor on that size and think that it might be reasonable. If you then cu=
t it back to $2.5 billion, people will get a sense of scarcity: =E2=80=98PS=
US thought there was $25 billion of demand but it=E2=80=99s only selling $2=
.5 billion of stock.=E2=80=99 That sense of scarcity will make people want =
to buy stock in the IPO, because they think it will trade up on aftermarket=
 demand: All the retail investors, etc., who expected=C2=A0$25 billion wort=
h of stock, will only be able to buy $2.5 billion after the IPO, and they=
=E2=80=99ll bid up the price. So investors will put in a lot of orders in t=
he IPO, hoping to get an allocation in a relatively small=C2=A0hot IPO. And=
 this will snowball: There will be so much demand for the IPO that PSUS wil=
l be able to price a $4 billion or $5 billion or $10 billion IPO that will =
still trade well.=E2=80=9DThat=E2=80=99s one possible story. That=E2=80=99s=
=C2=A0what=C2=A0Pershing Square might be trying to do, and=C2=A0the advice =
that its bankers might have given it about how to build momentum and get a =
lot of demand and make sure the stock trades well after the IPO.=C2=A0It is=
 not a story that the company would generally=C2=A0say explicitly in a pros=
pectus, for at least two reasons:=09Regulators don=E2=80=99t like you going=
 around=C2=A0telling=C2=A0investors that the stock will trade up. Prospectu=
ses tend to be more about financial information and risk warnings than they=
 are about =E2=80=9Chey if everyone buys this stock it=E2=80=99ll go up.=E2=
=80=9D=09It =E2=80=A6=C2=A0I mean =E2=80=A6 the point of this story is abou=
t investor psychology and anchoring and herd mentality, and it doesn=E2=80=
=99t work as well if you make it explicit. =E2=80=9CIf we first tell you $2=
5 billion, you=E2=80=99ll anchor on a big deal, and if we then tell you $2.=
5 billion you=E2=80=99ll get a sense of scarcity, and then everyone will=C2=
=A0put in orders because everyone else is putting in orders, so we=E2=80=99=
ll end up with a lot of momentum for a $10 billion deal=E2=80=9D: Isn=E2=80=
=99t=C2=A0the natural response to that to say =E2=80=9Cah, got it, I will d=
iscount the $25 billion thing and the $2.5 billion thing and not get too en=
thusiastic when other people put in orders=E2=80=9D?=C2=A0Here, though, is =
a letter that Ackman sent=C2=A0yesterday and that PSUS filed today:The $25=
=C2=A0billion number in the media initially anchored investors in thinking =
the deal would be too large.=C2=A0Ultimately, I expect this =E2=80=98anchor=
ing=E2=80=99 to be helpful to the final outcome. =E2=80=A6The nature of IPO=
 processes is such that they are highly momentum driven and back end loaded=
. ...The banks also play a very important role.=C2=A0=E2=80=A6 It is theref=
ore very important that the banks get a sense that a deal=E2=80=99s momentu=
m is building as they convey that feeling of momentum to the capital market=
s desks of every institutional investor, and the financial advisor communit=
y also wants to hear that the institutions are interested and motivated.We =
have told the market that the transaction will have a hard cap at $10=C2=A0=
billion. The typical approach is to show a small deal size to make market p=
articipants concerned that they will miss the deal if they don=E2=80=99t pu=
t their order in quickly. ...I expect that we will file a prospectus tomorr=
ow with a $2.5=E2=80=94$4=C2=A0billion cover.=C2=A0The ultimate deal size w=
ill depend on how demand builds Thursday, Friday and Monday. We will price =
Monday night unless we have to refile due to a material increase in the siz=
e of the deal above tomorrow=E2=80=99s filing range.None of these ideas are=
 exactly=C2=A0surprising, but it=E2=80=99s surprising to read them in=C2=A0=
a securities filing for an IPO. It was an accident, though: That letter was=
 sent to =E2=80=9Ca limited number of strategic institutional and high net =
worth investors in Pershing Square Holdco, L.P.,=E2=80=9D the=C2=A0manageme=
nt company that Ackman controls and that will run PSUS.
  [3]
=C2=A0It was not meant for every=C2=A0IPO investor, just for a few investor=
s who are close to Ackman; it was private commentary on the IPO tactics, no=
t an official marketing document. PSUS=E2=80=99s public=C2=A0filing has an =
awkward preface=C2=A0saying: =E2=80=9CMr. Ackman sent Appendix A [the lette=
r] as an internal communication to the investors in Pershing Square Holdco,=
 L.P. and therefore did not believe that it would require public disclosure=
.=E2=80=9D But apparently his=C2=A0lawyers disagreed, and now everyone can =
read it.Does it =E2=80=A6=C2=A0does it help? Does it =E2=80=9Cconvey that f=
eeling of momentum=E2=80=9D? The letter goes on to ask the strategic invest=
ors to put their orders in for the IPO:In light of all of the above, partic=
ipation by this illustrious group is important and extremely helpful to the=
 IPO. Three members of this group have already put in orders with the banks=
 for $25m, $50m and $100m. =E2=80=A6=C2=A0While we did not make it a requir=
ement for strategic investors to invest in PSUS, our hope was that our stra=
tegic investors would find the offering highly attractive and would partici=
pate in the IPO.In short, this is a moment when you can be very helpful to =
Pershing Square by participating in the PSUS offering and giving your order=
 to the banks, the sooner the better. An order today will enable us to impr=
ove the strength of tomorrow=E2=80=99s initial message to the market on dea=
l size. Orders that come later are of course still very helpful as the book=
 will build and we create momentum over the weekend into Monday.I feel like=
 explicitly asking your best investors to be =E2=80=9Cvery helpful=E2=80=9D=
 by putting in a big order to =E2=80=9Cimprove the strength of [the] messag=
e to the market on deal size=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Ccreate momentum=E2=80=9D=
 might have the opposite effect,=C2=A0if everyone can read the request? (Pa=
rticularly if the formerly maybe $25 billion IPO is now maybe a $2.5 billio=
n IPO?) The IPOs you really want to invest in are the ones where nobody has=
 to ask for your order.But Ackman is not just looking for momentum; he also=
 makes the case that the stock will trade up. Pershing Square=E2=80=99s exi=
sting European closed-end fund trades at a discount to net asset value, and=
 many US closed-end funds do too, making it a bit of a tough sell. (If you =
buy the stock at its $50 offering price, and it trades down to a 10% discou=
nt to NAV, you=E2=80=99re out $5 immediately.)=C2=A0But Ackman argues=C2=A0=
that PSUS is different from other closed-end funds=C2=A0and should trade at=
 a premium to NAV, and that there are =E2=80=9Cother powerful technicals in=
 our favor=E2=80=9D that will cause the stock to trade up after the IPO:We =
have a powerful case to make for aftermarket demand. We have explained to e=
very investor that this will not be our last public offering and that the s=
uccess of this offering is critical to the long-term ability of Pershing Sq=
uare Inc. to have successful future IPOs. We have committed to limit supply=
 versus potential demand so that the stock trades well in the aftermarket i=
ncluding announcing a hard cap on size at $10 billion. Going against this p=
erception is the fact that in all previous closed end fund IPOs the issuers=
 have met 100% of the demand stock. As a result, the post-IPO trading dynam=
ics of closed end funds are not a good reference point for what we are comm=
itting to achieve. ...Importantly, because of PSUS=E2=80=99s corporate stru=
cture, we are not permitted to offer the transaction to investors in the Eu=
ropean Union, as well as institutions in Norway, Korea, Kuwait, Malaysia, m=
arkets where Pershing Square is well known and where we have many current a=
nd former investors. In addition, non-U.S. retail is not permitted to buy s=
tock in the IPO. As a result, all of these ineligible IPO investors have to=
 buy stock in the aftermarket when the stock begins to trade. In addition, =
we believe that U.S. retail will be huge source of aftermarket demand.The l=
ast sentence might be the most important: Ackman has a big following among =
US retail investors, and probably many of them=C2=A0will not get shares in =
the IPO, so they will buy in the aftermarket and support the price. And the=
 smaller size will help with this: If PSUS raises $2.5 billion rather than =
$25 billion, there will be fewer shares for retail investors to buy in the =
aftermarket, so they will trade better.But if you are doing an IPO, you=C2=
=A0are not=C2=A0really=C2=A0supposed to go around=C2=A0saying publicly=C2=
=A0=E2=80=9Cthis stock will trade up after the IPO.=E2=80=9D Obviously that=
=E2=80=99s what investors want, but you can=E2=80=99t just, like, put in th=
e prospectus =E2=80=9Cwe promise you the stock will trade up.=E2=80=9D But =
Ackman says in his letter that =E2=80=9Cit requires a significant leap of f=
aith and ultimately careful analysis and judgment for investors to recogniz=
e that this closed end company will trade at a premium after the IPO when v=
ery few in history have done so,=E2=80=9D which I think is=C2=A0a promise t=
hat the stock will trade up? Not what regulators like to see.Because, again=
, he wasn=E2=80=99t expecting the letter to be public. But it is.=C2=A0So P=
SUS=E2=80=99s awkward preface to the letter goes on:You should not consider=
 the statements in the communication attached as Appendix A in making your =
investment decision with respect to the Offering, including, in particular:=
=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0 =C2=A0=E2=80=A2 The statements regarding the absence of =
key man risk. ...=E2=80=A2 The statements regarding the post-Offering tradi=
ng dynamics, including with respect to market demand, trading discounts or =
premiums or trading volume. Shares of closed-end investment companies frequ=
ently trade at a discount from their net asset value. =C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0 =
=C2=A0=E2=80=A2 The statements regarding indications of interest from inves=
tors and any investor=E2=80=99s rationale for participation or non-particip=
ation in the Offering. ...The Company specifically disclaims the statements=
 made by Mr. Ackman.The letter contains arguments=C2=A0that the stock will =
trade well, but it=E2=80=99s not supposed to, and PSUS =E2=80=9Cspecificall=
y disclaims=E2=80=9D them. Officially, PSUS wants you to know that =E2=80=
=9Cshares of closed-end investment companies frequently trade at a discount=
,=E2=80=9D and you should ignore PSUS=E2=80=99s chief executive officer whe=
n he says that this one won=E2=80=99t. I have never read an IPO prospectus =
that winked=C2=A0before, but I think this one might.
