      Everything is securities fraud
   =20
 =20
=E2=80=9CEvery bad thing that a public company does is also securities frau=
d,=E2=80=9D I like to say around here, and CrowdStrike Holdings Inc. shippe=
d a really bad software bug last week:CrowdStrike Holdings Inc., the cybers=
ecurity company at the center of massive global IT outages, said that a bug=
 in a quality-assurance tool the company uses to check updates for mistakes=
 allowed flawed data to go out to customers, causing last week=E2=80=99s me=
ltdown.On Friday, the company pushed through an update for Windows machines=
 via a rapid-response mechanism, meant to respond quickly to changing threa=
ts. That update contained a critical flaw. CrowdStrike=E2=80=99s =E2=80=9Cc=
ontent validator,=E2=80=9D which is supposed to test updates for errors bef=
ore they go out, malfunctioned and let the bug pass through, the company sa=
id in an incident report published on Wednesday.That undetected error crash=
ed Windows systems and kicked off one of the most spectacular rolling IT fa=
ilures in history. The US company is trying to piece together the series of=
 events that led to crashed Microsoft Windows computer systems around the w=
orld, taking down airline, banking and stock exchange operations from Austr=
alia and Japan to the UK.From Thursday=E2=80=99s close (before the bug) to =
Monday=E2=80=99s, CrowdStrike=E2=80=99s stock fell about 23%. That=E2=80=99=
s as classic a case of =E2=80=9Ceverything is securities fraud=E2=80=9D as =
you are going to get: CrowdStrike messed something up, its stock fell, ther=
e will be lawsuits. So far I have not seen any lawsuits, but here are five=
=C2=A0press releases from law firms looking for CrowdStrike shareholders to=
 sue, so give it a few days.=C2=A0Elsewhere, Jonathan Weil argues that =E2=
=80=9CCrowdStrike=E2=80=99s disastrous software update ought to put its fin=
ancial reporting, not just its product issues, under an unwelcome spotlight=
,=E2=80=9D since its reporting emphasizes annual recurring revenue, and tha=
t ARR calculation =E2=80=94=C2=A0which assumes that expired contracts will =
be renewed =E2=80=94=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cmay be a stretch, considering that Crowd=
Strike=E2=80=99s botched software update just caused a global computer outa=
ge, likely prompting many to rethink their existing contracts.=E2=80=9D I s=
uppose that=E2=80=99s a good hook =E2=80=94=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cyour annual recur=
ring revenue is not as recurring as you said it was=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0for the everything-is-securities-fraud lawsuits.I also often add that ev=
ery bad thing that=C2=A0happens to=C2=A0a public company can be securities =
fraud, and CrowdStrike=E2=80=99s botched software update definitely happene=
d to a lot of public companies. I have not yet seen any lawyers trawling fo=
r clients to sue Delta Air Lines Inc., but it =E2=80=9Cis expected to take =
a sizable financial hit this quarter from the system breakdown that led to =
thousands of canceled flights and prompted a federal investigation of the c=
arrier=E2=80=99s response,=E2=80=9D so look out for that one too.
