</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Every initial public offering is marke=
ted in two ways:</p><ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40=
px; margin: 16px 0;">=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">=E2=80=9CThis com=
pany is good=E2=80=9D: This is the story that the IPO prospectus will tell,=
 and that the company will tell in roadshow meetings with potential investo=
rs. The company has a good business, a good product,=C2=A0smart managers, s=
trong financial results, so if you are a long-term fundamental investor you=
 should buy some stock.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">=E2=80=9CT=
his stock will trade up=E2=80=9D: This is the story that the marginal inves=
tor in the IPO wants to hear. The company is selling X million shares in th=
e IPO, there are orders for 10X million shares, there are a lot of retail i=
nvestors who would love to buy it but can=E2=80=99t get into the IPO, and s=
o, when the stock opens for trading on the day after the IPO, lots of peopl=
e =E2=80=94=C2=A0the retail investors, the people who put in the 9X million=
 orders that weren=E2=80=99t filled =E2=80=94=C2=A0will buy it in the after=
market. There is a lot of demand, not enough supply, so the stock will go u=
p.</li></ol><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That second story is, to some degr=
ee, self-fulfilling. The company=E2=80=99s banks will call an investor to a=
sk=C2=A0=E2=80=9Chow much do you want to buy in this IPO?=E2=80=9D The inve=
stor will say =E2=80=9Cwell how is it going?=E2=80=9D The correct answer is=
 not =E2=80=9Cwe=E2=80=99ve got orders for 80% of the shares, so it would r=
eally help if you=E2=80=99d put in a big order for the other 20%.=E2=80=9D =
The answer the investor wants is more like =E2=80=9Cwe=E2=80=99ve got order=
s for 1,000% of the shares, but if you put in a big order we=E2=80=99ll see=
 what we can do for you.=E2=80=9D The more demand the investors think there=
 is, the more demand there will actually be: Investors want to buy into IPO=
s that=C2=A0<em>don=E2=80=99t=C2=A0</em>need their money, because those are=
 the ones that will trade up.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-=
1" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom=
-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !impor=
tant; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a></p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">We have <a href=3D"https://link.mail.b=
loombergbusiness.com/click/36186471.204172/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNv=
bS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjQtMDItMDgvYmlsbC1hY2ttYW4td2FudHMteW91ci1tb25=
leT9jbXBpZD1CQkQwNzI1MjRfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2=
U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yNDA3MjUmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f0=
7ceef4b8524a319a23cBf0e0efaf" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope=
" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !importa=
nt; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-s=
tyle: solid; background-color: #ccc;">talked</a> a <a href=3D"https://link.=
mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/36186471.204172/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZX=
JnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjQtMDYtMDYvYmlsbC1hY2ttYW4td2FudHMtYS1sb=
3Qtb2YteW91ci1tb25leT9jbXBpZD1CQkQwNzI1MjRfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVt=
YWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yNDA3MjUmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1=
vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBbc111f04" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" item=
scope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decorat=
ion: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #00000=
0; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">few</a> <a href=3D"=
https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/36186471.204172/aHR0cHM6Ly93d=
3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjQtMDctMTYvYmlsbC1hY2ttYW4t=
Y2FuLXR3ZWV0LWhpcy1uZXctZnVuZD9jbXBpZD1CQkQwNzI1MjRfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWV=
kaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yNDA3MjUmdXRtX2NhbX=
BhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB0d5efae7" itemprop=3D"StoryL=
ink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; tex=
t-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-colo=
r: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">times</a> =
about Bill Ackman=E2=80=99s plans for a US publicly listed closed-end fund,=
 Pershing Square USA Ltd., or PSUS. He has=C2=A0talked about=C2=A0<a href=
=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/36186471.204172/aHR0cHM6L=
y93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjQtMDctMTEvYWNrbWFuLXRvdXRz=
LWJlcmtzaGlyZS1hcy1tb2RlbC1mb3ItY2xvc2VkLWVuZC1mdW5kLWFoZWFkLW9mLWlwbz9jbXB=
pZD1CQkQwNzI1MjRfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2=
xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yNDA3MjUmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8=
524a319a23cB8f8cfd4a" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=
=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bord=
er-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: so=
lid; background-color: #ccc;">raising $25 billion</a> in its IPO.=C2=A0He=
=E2=80=99s marketing that IPO now, and the roadshow is nearing its end, wit=
h the deal set to price on Monday. So far, uh, it doesn=E2=80=99t look like=
 $25 billion.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-2" style=3D"colo=
r: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; bor=
der-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background=
-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[2]</span>
</a>=C2=A0The <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/3618=
6471.204172/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjQtMDc=
tMjUvYWNrbWFuLWV5ZXMtNC1iaWxsaW9uLWZvci1jbG9zZWQtZW5kLWZ1bmQtd2VsbC1zaG9ydC=
1vZi1nb2FsP2NtcGlkPUJCRDA3MjUyNF9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX=
3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTI0MDcyNSZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVm=
Zg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB3e0c8c94" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"i=
temscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none =
!important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-=
bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">revised target</a> is more li=
ke $2.5 billion to $4 billion, with room to grow from there but=C2=A0a hard=
 cap of $10 billion.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I suppose you could te=
ll a version of Story 2 here that would go something like this: =E2=80=9CIf=
 the market gets the idea that PSUS will be a $25 billion IPO, people will =
anchor on that size and think that it might be reasonable. If you then cut =
it back to $2.5 billion, people will get a sense of scarcity: =E2=80=98PSUS=
 thought there was $25 billion of demand but it=E2=80=99s only selling $2.5=
 billion of stock.=E2=80=99 That sense of scarcity will make people want to=
 buy stock in the IPO, because they think it will trade up on aftermarket d=
emand: All the retail investors, etc., who expected=C2=A0$25 billion worth =
of stock, will only be able to buy $2.5 billion after the IPO, and they=E2=
=80=99ll bid up the price. So investors will put in a lot of orders in the =
IPO, hoping to get an allocation in a relatively small=C2=A0hot IPO. And th=
is will snowball: There will be so much demand for the IPO that PSUS will b=
e able to price a $4 billion or $5 billion or $10 billion IPO that will sti=
ll trade well.=E2=80=9D</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That=E2=80=99s one =
possible story. That=E2=80=99s=C2=A0what=C2=A0Pershing Square might be tryi=
ng to do, and=C2=A0the advice that its bankers might have given it about ho=
w to build momentum and get a lot of demand and make sure the stock trades =
well after the IPO.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It is not a story=
 that the company would generally=C2=A0<em>say explicitly in a prospectus</=
em>, for at least two reasons:</p><ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; pa=
dding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Reg=
ulators don=E2=80=99t like you going around=C2=A0<em>telling=C2=A0</em>inve=
stors that the stock will trade up. Prospectuses tend to be more about fina=
ncial information and risk warnings than they are about =E2=80=9Chey if eve=
ryone buys this stock it=E2=80=99ll go up.=E2=80=9D</li>=09<li style=3D"mar=
gin-bottom: 5px;">It =E2=80=A6=C2=A0I mean =E2=80=A6 the point of this stor=
y is about investor psychology and anchoring and herd mentality, and it doe=
sn=E2=80=99t work as well if you make it explicit. =E2=80=9CIf we first tel=
l you $25 billion, you=E2=80=99ll anchor on a big deal, and if we then tell=
 you $2.5 billion you=E2=80=99ll get a sense of scarcity, and then everyone=
 will=C2=A0put in orders because everyone else is putting in orders, so we=
=E2=80=99ll end up with a lot of momentum for a $10 billion deal=E2=80=9D: =
Isn=E2=80=99t=C2=A0the natural response to that to say =E2=80=9Cah, got it,=
 I will discount the $25 billion thing and the $2.5 billion thing and not g=
et too enthusiastic when other people put in orders=E2=80=9D?=C2=A0</li></o=
l><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here, though, is a letter that Ackman sent=
=C2=A0yesterday and that <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com=
/click/36186471.204172/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9BcmNoaXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRh=
LzIwMDI2NjAvMDAwMTE5MzEyNTI0MTg0MjU2L2Q4MTM1NDBkZndwLmh0bQ/607f07ceef4b8524=
a319a23cBe1f809cb" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D=
"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-=
bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid=
; background-color: #ccc;">PSUS filed today</a>:</p><blockquote><p style=3D=
"margin: 16px 0;">The $25=C2=A0billion number in the media initially anchor=
ed investors in thinking the deal would be too large.=C2=A0Ultimately, I ex=
pect this =E2=80=98anchoring=E2=80=99 to be helpful to the final outcome. =
=E2=80=A6</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The nature of IPO processes is su=
ch that they are highly momentum driven and back end loaded. ...</p><p styl=
e=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The banks also play a very important role.=C2=A0=E2=
=80=A6 It is therefore very important that the banks get a sense that a dea=
l=E2=80=99s momentum is building as they convey that feeling of momentum to=
 the capital markets desks of every institutional investor, and the financi=
al advisor community also wants to hear that the institutions are intereste=
d and motivated.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">We have told the market th=
at the transaction will have a hard cap at $10=C2=A0billion. The typical ap=
proach is to show a small deal size to make market participants concerned t=
hat they will miss the deal if they don=E2=80=99t put their order in quickl=
y. ...</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I expect that we will file a prospec=
tus tomorrow with a $2.5=E2=80=94$4=C2=A0billion cover.=C2=A0The ultimate d=
eal size will depend on how demand builds Thursday, Friday and Monday. We w=
ill price Monday night unless we have to refile due to a material increase =
in the size of the deal above tomorrow=E2=80=99s filing range.</p></blockqu=
ote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">None of these ideas are exactly=C2=A0surpr=
ising, but it=E2=80=99s surprising to read them in=C2=A0a securities filing=
 for an IPO. It was an accident, though: That letter was sent to =E2=80=9Ca=
 limited number of strategic institutional and high net worth investors in =
Pershing Square Holdco, L.P.,=E2=80=9D the=C2=A0management company that Ack=
man controls and that will run PSUS.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#fo=
otnote-3" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border=
-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none=
 !important; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-bloc=
k;">
<span>[3]</span>
</a>=C2=A0It was not meant for <em>every=C2=A0</em>IPO investor, just for a=
 few investors who are close to Ackman; it was private commentary on the IP=
O tactics, not an official marketing document. PSUS=E2=80=99s public=C2=A0f=
iling has an awkward preface=C2=A0saying: =E2=80=9CMr. Ackman sent Appendix=
 A [the letter] as an internal communication to the investors in Pershing S=
quare Holdco, L.P. and therefore did not believe that it would require publ=
ic disclosure.=E2=80=9D But apparently his=C2=A0lawyers disagreed, and now =
everyone can read it.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Does it =E2=80=A6=C2=
=A0does it help? Does it =E2=80=9Cconvey that feeling of momentum=E2=80=9D?=
 The letter goes on to ask the strategic investors to put their orders in f=
or the IPO:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In light of all of =
the above, participation by this illustrious group is important and extreme=
ly helpful to the IPO. Three members of this group have already put in orde=
rs with the banks for $25m, $50m and $100m. =E2=80=A6=C2=A0While we did not=
 make it a requirement for strategic investors to invest in PSUS, our hope =
was that our strategic investors would find the offering highly attractive =
and would participate in the IPO.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In short,=
 this is a moment when you can be very helpful to Pershing Square by partic=
ipating in the PSUS offering and giving your order to the banks, the sooner=
 the better. An order today will enable us to improve the strength of tomor=
row=E2=80=99s initial message to the market on deal size. Orders that come =
later are of course still very helpful as the book will build and we create=
 momentum over the weekend into Monday.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin:=
 16px 0;">I feel like explicitly asking your best investors to be =E2=80=9C=
very helpful=E2=80=9D by putting in a big order to =E2=80=9Cimprove the str=
ength of [the] message to the market on deal size=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Ccre=
ate momentum=E2=80=9D might have the opposite effect,=C2=A0<em>if everyone =
can read the request? </em>(Particularly if the formerly maybe $25 billion =
IPO is now maybe a $2.5 billion IPO?) The IPOs you really want to invest in=
 are the ones where nobody has to ask for your order.</p><p style=3D"margin=
: 16px 0;">But Ackman is not just looking for momentum; he also makes the c=
ase that the stock will trade up. Pershing Square=E2=80=99s existing Europe=
an closed-end fund trades at a discount to net asset value, and many US clo=
sed-end funds do too, making it a bit of a tough sell. (If you buy the stoc=
k at its <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/36186471.=
204172/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9BcmNoaXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRhLzIwMDI2NjAvMDAw=
MTE5MzEyNTI0MTcwOTE3L2Q2MjM3ODFkbjJhLmh0bQ/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB1f32a0c=
c" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=
=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-c=
olor: #ccc;">$50 offering price</a>, and it trades down to a 10% discount t=
o NAV, you=E2=80=99re out $5 immediately.)=C2=A0But Ackman argues=C2=A0that=
 PSUS is different from other closed-end funds=C2=A0and should trade at a p=
remium to NAV, and that there are =E2=80=9Cother powerful technicals in our=
 favor=E2=80=9D that will cause the stock to trade up after the IPO:</p><bl=
ockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">We have a powerful case to make for a=
ftermarket demand. We have explained to every investor that this will not b=
e our last public offering and that the success of this offering is critica=
l to the long-term ability of Pershing Square Inc. to have successful futur=
e IPOs. We have committed to limit supply versus potential demand so that t=
he stock trades well in the aftermarket including announcing a hard cap on =
size at $10 billion. Going against this perception is the fact that in all =
previous closed end fund IPOs the issuers have met 100% of the demand stock=
. As a result, the post-IPO trading dynamics of closed end funds are not a =
good reference point for what we are committing to achieve. ...</p><p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Importantly, because of PSUS=E2=80=99s corporate struc=
ture, we are not permitted to offer the transaction to investors in the Eur=
opean Union, as well as institutions in Norway, Korea, Kuwait, Malaysia, ma=
rkets where Pershing Square is well known and where we have many current an=
d former investors. In addition, non-U.S. retail is not permitted to buy st=
ock in the IPO. As a result, all of these ineligible IPO investors have to =
buy stock in the aftermarket when the stock begins to trade. In addition, w=
e believe that U.S. retail will be huge source of aftermarket demand.</p></=
blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The last sentence might be the most=
 important: Ackman has a big following among US retail investors, and proba=
bly many of them=C2=A0will not get shares in the IPO, so they will buy in t=
he aftermarket and support the price. And the smaller size will help with t=
his: If PSUS raises $2.5 billion rather than $25 billion, there will be few=
er shares for retail investors to buy in the aftermarket, so they will trad=
e better.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But if you are doing an IPO, you=
=C2=A0are not=C2=A0<em>really=C2=A0</em>supposed to go around=C2=A0<em>sayi=
ng publicly=C2=A0</em>=E2=80=9Cthis stock will trade up after the IPO.=E2=
=80=9D Obviously that=E2=80=99s what investors want, but you can=E2=80=99t =
just, like, put in the prospectus =E2=80=9Cwe promise you the stock will tr=
ade up.=E2=80=9D But Ackman says in his letter that =E2=80=9Cit requires a =
significant leap of faith and ultimately careful analysis and judgment for =
investors to recognize that this closed end company will trade at a premium=
 after the IPO when very few in history have done so,=E2=80=9D which I thin=
k <em>is</em>=C2=A0a promise that the stock will trade up? Not what regulat=
ors like to see.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Because, again, he wasn=E2=
=80=99t expecting the letter to be public. But it is.=C2=A0So PSUS=E2=80=99=
s awkward preface to the letter goes on:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin:=
 16px 0;">You should not consider the statements in the communication attac=
hed as Appendix A in making your investment decision with respect to the Of=
fering, including, in particular:=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0 =C2=A0</p><p style=3D"m=
argin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=A2 The statements regarding the absence of key man r=
isk. ...</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=A2 The statements regarding=
 the post-Offering trading dynamics, including with respect to market deman=
d, trading discounts or premiums or trading volume. Shares of closed-end in=
vestment companies frequently trade at a discount from their net asset valu=
e. =C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0 =C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=A2 The =
statements regarding indications of interest from investors and any investo=
r=E2=80=99s rationale for participation or non-participation in the Offerin=
g. ...</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The Company specifically disclaims t=
he statements made by Mr. Ackman.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px =
0;">The letter contains arguments=C2=A0that the stock will trade well, but =
it=E2=80=99s not supposed to, and PSUS =E2=80=9Cspecifically disclaims=E2=
=80=9D them. Officially, PSUS wants you to know that =E2=80=9Cshares of clo=
sed-end investment companies frequently trade at a discount,=E2=80=9D and y=
ou should ignore PSUS=E2=80=99s chief executive officer when he says that t=
his one won=E2=80=99t. I have never read an IPO prospectus that <em>winked=
=C2=A0</em>before, but I think this one might.</p><table class=3D"liveinten=
